\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Useful for quickly adding ramps between 'nodes'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Useful for smoothing transitions between CCs that were drawn at low resolution.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script starts with a dialog box in which the user can set:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab the lane to use ("under mouse" at start of script, or "last clicked")\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab the CC density (using either the MIDI editor's grid or the default value in Preferences -> CC density),\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab the shape of the ramp (as a sine, linear or power function),\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab whether the new events should be selected, and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab whether redundant events should be skipped.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (Any extraneous CCs between selected events are deleted)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the velocity lane, the script will not insert new notes, but will set velocities of existing notes to ramp from leftmost and rightmost notes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For faster one-click execution, skip the dialog box by setting "showDialogBox" to "false" in the USER AREA.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The default ramp properties can also be defined in the USER AREA.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Combine with warping script to easily insert all kinds of weird shapes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two ways in which this script can be run:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab First, the script can be linked to its own shortcut key.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Second, this script, together with other "js_" scripts that edit the "lane under mouse",can each be linked to a toolbar button.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab In this case, each script need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "js_Run the js_'lane under mouse' script that is selected in toolbar.lua" script needs to be linked to a keyboard shortcut (as well as a mousewheel shortcut).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Clicking the toolbar button will 'arm' the linked script (and the button will light up), and this selected (armed) script can then be run by using the shortcut for the aforementioned "js_Run..." script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For further instructions - please refer to the "js_Run..." script.\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
